int32 OS_ShellOutputToFile(const char *Cmd, osal_id_t filedes)
{
    OS_object_token_t token;
    int32             return_code;

    /* Check Parameters */
    OS_CHECK_POINTER(Cmd);

    return_code = OS_ObjectIdGetById(OS_LOCK_MODE_REFCOUNT, OS_OBJECT_TYPE_OS_STREAM, filedes, &token);
    if (return_code == OS_SUCCESS)
    {
        return_code = OS_ShellOutputToFile_Impl(&token, Cmd);
        OS_ObjectIdRelease(&token);
    }

    return return_code;
}

int32 OS_ObjectIdGetById(OS_lock_mode_t lock_mode, osal_objtype_t idtype, osal_id_t id, OS_object_token_t *token)
{
    int32 return_code;

    return_code = OS_ObjectIdTransactionInit(lock_mode, idtype, token);
    if (return_code != OS_SUCCESS)
    {
        return return_code;
    }

    return_code = OS_ObjectIdToArrayIndex(idtype, id, &token->obj_idx);
    if (return_code == OS_SUCCESS)
    {
        token->obj_id = id;

        /*
         * The "ConvertToken" routine will return with the global lock
         * in a state appropriate for returning to the caller, as indicated
         * by the "check_mode" parameter.
         *
         * Note If this operation fails, then it always unlocks the global for
         * all check_mode's other than NONE.
         */
        return_code = OS_ObjectIdConvertToken(token);
    }

    if (return_code != OS_SUCCESS)
    {
        OS_ObjectIdTransactionCancel(token);
    }

    return return_code;
}
...
void OS_ObjectIdRelease(OS_object_token_t *token)
{
    OS_ObjectIdTransactionFinish(token, NULL);
}

explanation: I examined the provided code fragments for any use of the Standard Library function memcmp to compare null-terminated strings (MISRA C 2023 Rule 21.14). No calls to memcmp appear in the shown code. The only pointer check is the macro OS_CHECK_POINTER(Cmd) which expands to a NULL pointer test ((ptr) != NULL) — this is not a memcmp string comparison. The OS_ShellOutputToFile function merely forwards Cmd to OS_ShellOutputToFile_Impl; the provided Impl stub returns OS_ERR_NOT_IMPLEMENTED and contains no string operations. The other shown routines (OS_ObjectIdGetById, OS_ObjectIdRelease) perform integer/index checks and token handling, not string comparisons with memcmp. Therefore there are no code fragments in the supplied code that violate Rule 21.14. If there are other source files or implementations (for example the real OS_ShellOutputToFile_Impl or other omitted routines indicated by ellipses) those were not provided; they would need to be inspected separately for any memcmp usage on null-terminated strings.
